post_text: Our staff is so excited to see students tomorrow! Parents and students- you should have received an email today with detailed info- including where students enter the building, how 6-12th grades get locker assignments and chromebooks and where report to at the beginning of the school day. If you don’t have it, never fear! It’s posted multiple places within the building. Remember your mask, water bottle, and that students can enter building at 7:40. School starts at 8 am sharp! This week we will have a 1:30 dismissal. It’s always a great day to be an Essex Trojan!! You also might notice the view is a little different to the East as basement/construction has begun on the house the construction trades program will be building!

post_text: Just a reminder, and some information on how the first day of school will go. Students can arrive at school after 7:40. School starts at 8 am. Those who wish to eat breakfast will grab it and go to their classrooms. Prek-2 enter north doors, 3-5 middle doors (by tag/title 1 rooms), 6-8 at far south front doors, 9-12 main doors (this is a change from info you might have seen previously!). Temperatures will be taken of all students and staff. On Wednesday- the first day of school, 6-12 grade students go to the grade level home rooms! (Listed below). Helpers at the door will also have info and be able to direct you! Take all of your stuff and you will find out your locker number and have time to take items to locker during that hour. Reminder - 1:30 dismissal the first 3 days! Bring your masks and water bottles!! Staff is back in the building today getting ready to see you all- we are so excited!!

post_text:
The Essex Community School student school supply list is available. Please note that headphones/earbuds are needed for grades K-12 (there will NOT be ones available on loan through the library anymore). Small bottles of hand sanitizer for your student's use are recommended, as well as a mask (needed during entry to building, in hallway & at times social distancing is not possible). Please contact the school with any questions, at 379-3114.
Also note: School starts August 26th, and August 26, 27, 28 there will be a 1:30 dismissal, as show on our district calendar. After that (beginning August 31st) normal hours are 8 am to 3:30 pm Monday-Thursday, and 8 am to 1:30 pm on Fridays. This is a change from our schedules in the past!!! (students can arrive on school grounds starting at 7:40 am) Please be sure to check the website at www.essex.k12.ia.us for continued up-to-date information.
http://www.essex.k12.ia.us/files/8715/9658/9744/School_Supply_List.pdf

post_text: Reminder - today 5-8 pm, tomorrow (5/22) from 7-10 am all families may return their school items (chromebooks/chargers, iPads, whiteboards, textbooks, library books, etc) AND pick up items left in desks and lockers at school. We ask that you take advantage of these time frames and return items so they can be readied for the fall. Social distancing and safety measures will be taken - we ask that people not get out of their vehicles, and pull into the drive in front of school. Have your child’s items bagged up and labeled, ready to be handed to us, and we have done the same with the items at school. Thank you!!

post_text: As a reminder - school board meetings are available via Zoom at this time, or in person. The zoom link is on the official agenda published before the meeting, and is also on the school website. Attendance at the in person meeting is limited to 10 or less people, due to state regulations (the board and officials would be a good portion of the 10) and minors must attend via zoom - not in person, as students are not able to be in the school building the remainder of the school year. Thank you!

post_text:
During the month of May we are going to pay a little extra attention to our 2020 seniors. Starting next week will highlight each senior individually - one day we will post a baby photo together with a memory, the second day we will reveal the senior and their future plans. This will culminate with a parade on May 17, what would have been their graduation date. On that day seniors will don cap and gown and stand along Main Street in Essex starting at noon. We invite all to drive past, honk, wave. There are 8 seniors, if you would like to “adopt” any or all of them with a note of encouragement, card, or gift or gift card. Please reach out to johnsontaylor@essex.k12.ia.us for information on where to direct it to. Or deliver personally on May 17 while keeping social distance. 2020
Seniors are: Kelli Baker, Ainsley Byers, Camryn Chambers, Jasmine Fort, Samantha Hedditch, Caden Henderson, Wesley Johnson, and Allison Smith. We hope to celebrate them at a graduation date later this summer, with logistics dependent upon restrictions at that time.

post_text: Good afternoon. As you know the corona virus is spreading in our state and across the country. The virus has been found to stay alive on plastic and metals so it is recommended cities and schools close playgrounds. We want to make sure we are doing our part to prevent the spread of the virus in our community. As a result of this information, the Essex school playground will be closed until further notice. If you have any questions, please contact me at wellsm@essex.k12.ia.us. Thank you for helping us keep our community safe. God Bless you and your family during this time and remember if you need anything please contact me. Thank you. Dr. Wells, Essex superintendent.

post_text: We may not be able to gather, but we can all take part in this activity!
shared_text:
Essex Community Club
March 21 at 10:53 AM ·

Ready to “go on a bear hunt”? Or help with a fun (safe) event? Starting today, through March 29 put a teddy bear, or a picture of a bear, in a window visible from the street. Our goal? To create a fun activity that kids and families can do, to relieve boredom, but in a safe way. As they walk the streets of Essex, they “hunt” for bears, or whatever the theme of the week is. A map of Essex so the more devoted hunters can mark their finds, or paths covered, is coming! But the fun doesn’t end there - March 29–April 5 will be “chalk your walk” (get out and decorate your sidewalk in positive or uplifting words. A happy face in a window works too if you don’t have chalk or ability to get out). April 5- 12 will be a “Easter egg hunt” with pictures of Easter eggs in windows. Then April 12-19 brings flowers - real or pictures. Thanks to all who helped bring this idea to Essex, and all who participate to make it fun!!

post_text: Our school calendar is UPDATED to include times for "classes" (aka Zoom video with teachers), that I have currently. Please see www.essex.k12.ia.us & click "Calendar" & choose the Master Calendar. In addition to the Zoom videos, secondary students are expected to check their email and google classroom daily (M-F). While the classrooms at the school were empty today, learning isn't over and Essex staff is excited to use technology to help our students continue to grow. We are all learning together on how this will work best! Parents are a HUGE part of the learning that will be taking place, so please reach out to teachers with any concerns. (all staff emails are listed on our webpage!) Dr Wells has a list of students with lack of internet - please email him if you need added to the list (wellsm@essex.k12.ia.us). Any technical issues with chromebooks/ipads please reach out to chambersm@essex.k12.ia.us You can also always leave a message at the school 712-379-3114 as someone will be there weekdays to return calls.

post_text:
Are you a selfie fanatic? Do you prefer the outstretched arm method, or do you enlist the help of a selfie stick? Essex Computer Graphics students Wesley Johnson, Dylan Barrett, Isaiah Kline, Andrew Arnold and Trevor Good are exploring the use of a third option, a selfie “drone” technically a remote-control quadcopter with a camera on it by AirSelfie 2. Equipped with its own built in Wi-Fi hotspot, the pocket-size flying camera connects to your smartphone via the AirSelfie 2 App and allows you to take boundless HD photos of you, your friends, and your life from the sky.

Students have been taking pictures at pep rallies, around our school and community and recording glimpses of student life all to be used in creating an Essex promotional graphic to be given to the Community Partnership Committee.

post_text:
Next week is Winter Homecoming in Essex. There will be a week full of events Mon-Friday, including themed dress up days and dodgeball tournament for JH/HS. The week culminates with home basketball game Friday, fundraiser dinner for JH Boosters, Coronation of Winter Homecoming Royalty & recognition of the court, with the HS dance the following evening.
Winter Homecoming Dress Up Days - ELEMENTARY (pre-5)
Monday: Stay Warm and Snuggly (Pajama Day)
Tuesday: Keep your Brain Warm (wear a stocking hat)
Wednesday: Polar Bear Day (bring a stuffed bear)
Thursday: Snow Day (wear white or snowflakes)
Friday: Trojan Pride Day (wear red, black and white)

Winter Homecoming Dress Up Days JH/HS (6-12)
Mon: Status Day (wear green/single; wear yellow/talking; wear red/taken)
Tues: Stereotype Day!
Wed: Color Day (6th gr/orange; 7th gr/green; 8th gr/yellow; 9th gr/blue; 10th gr/black; Jr/red; Sr/white)
Thurs: Fake an Injury Day
Fri: Spirit Day (dress up in your Trojan gear)

post_text: What a busy week leading up to our Winter Break! (after today's 1:15 dismissal we will return on January 3rd!) Yesterday our elementary students picked 2 presents for family members, as shown in another post, and then went to watch a movie in the afternoon. Today, our Student Council delivered trays full of goodies as a "Thank you" to area businesses for their support of our school & activities, and also delivered our food drive items to the food pantry. Classroom parties were held today, with elem. doing a rotation through each room where a teacher had an activity. Our JH/HS students participated in a beach ball volleyball tournament during homeroom this week, and also threw a farewell party for Mr. Heinhold, who student taught with us the first half of the year. And all week we had dress up days! Tonight are home basketball games, and a tailgate supper - the fun isn't over yet! and students can attend 5th quarter at the East Gym after the games!

post_text: It is a busy (short) week. Today - some of our JH students headed off to the Corner Conf. Science Fair. Good luck to them! Our 6th graders are taking a huge step back in time today. They are going to setup a Living History Museum for the rest of the school, and public, to visit. If you'd like to see their hard work in action, stop by the school from 1:00-3:45 PM (in the Media Center). If you haven't experienced a Living History Museum, you can expect to see our students recreating historical settings/people to simulate past time period.
